body:
I've been experimenting with JSDoc3 to see if I could alleviate some of the concerns you've raised @ellisonbg. I think I may have been able to alleviate one of them, but I think I could use some more clarification as well.

> -  Complex multiline comment formatting is required. You can't "just write".

``` javascript
/**
Represents a cat.
@param {string} color - The cat's fur color.
@param {int} age - the cat's age.
@constructor
*/
function Cat(color, age) {
  this.fur  = color;
  this.age = age;
  /** Commands the cat to meow */
  this.meow = function() {
     alert("meow");
   }
}
```

Does the example avoid the complex formatting you were speaking of? I took that to mean comments that look like this . . .

``` javascript
/**
* Represents a cat.
* @param {string} color - The cat's fur color.
* @param {int} age -  The cat's age.
* @constructor
*/
```

I too hate having to slap all those useless stars into my comments so I was pleased to find that I didn't have to with JSDoc3, I only have to start my comments with `/**`. If I have things I **don't** want JSDoc to parse I could use `//` or `/*`` with any other amount of stars besides 2.

Now that I think of it, are do you dislike the whole `@param` stuff? I feel like having a convention like this that contributors can all unanimously look to as the standard could be very useful. Let me know what you think!
